b'' b'the following is a juxtaposition of part of an ancient text known as' b'"de sacramentis", usually attributed to st. ambrose of milan, and the' b'canon of the traditional catholic mass of the roman rite. the' b'conclusion from this comparison is that the central part of the' b'traditional roman canon was already fairly well in place by sometime' b'in the late 4th century.' b'' b'taken from "the mass of the western rites", by the right reverend dom' b'fernand cabrol, abbot of farnborough, without permission.' b'excerpted from chapter vi: the mass at rome, from the fifth to the' b'seventh centuries. the paragraph at the end is from the book, not me.' b'' b'sorry about the long lines.' b'' b'joe buehler' b'' b'-----' b'' b'text of de sacramentis roman canon roman canon' b'(about ad) ad) (english translation)' b'' b'te igitur (omitted here)' b'memento domine b'communicantes b'hanc igitur oblationem b'' b'fac nobis (inquit sacerdos), quam oblationem tu deus, in do thou, o god, deign to' b'hanc oblationem ascriptam, omnibus, quaesumus, bless what we offer, and' b'ratam, rationabilem, benedictam, adscriptam, make it approved,' b'acceptabilem, quod figura ratam, rationabilem, effective, right, and' b'est corporis et sanguinis acceptabilemque facere wholly pleasing in every' b'jesu christi. digneris: ut nobis corpus et way, that it may become' b'sanguis fiat dilectissimi for our good, the body' b'filii tui domini nostri jesu and blood of thy dearly' b'christi. beloved son, jesus christ' b'our lord.' b'' b'qui pridie quam pateretur, qui pridie quam pateretur, who, the day before he' b'in sanctis manibus suis accepit panem in sanctas ac suffered, took bread into' b'accepit panem, respexit in venerabiles manus suas: et his holy and venerable' b'caelum ad te, sancte pater elevatis oculis in ccelum, hands, and having raised' b'omnipotens, aeterne deus, ad te deum patrem suum his eyes to heaven, unto' b'gratias agens, benedixit, omnipotentem, tibi gratias thee, o god, his alm