tions of the same' b'text; and as that of de sacramentis is localised in upper italy' b'and dated about the year it is the most ancient witness we' b'possess as to the principal parts of the roman canon, which only' b'appear in the sacramentaries some time after the seventh' b'century. the question as to whether the roman canon is not older' b'even than that of de sacramentis is discussed by' b'liturgiologists. mgr. batiffol is of this opinion, but we, on' b'the contrary, think that the former bears traces of closer' b'composition, of a more carefully guarded orthodoxy, and that' b'consequently it is a text corrected from de sacramentis. we' b'shall see, in studying the list of names in the memento of the' b'living and that of the dead, that mgr. batiffol argues with good' b'reason that he can date these fragments from the pontificate of' b'symmachus we thus have the state of the roman mass,' b'or at least of the chief parts of the canon, at the beginning of' b'the fourth century.' 